-- Chapter 1: Your product — comes before all deal mechanics
-- These concepts force the reckoning that most STEM founders skip.

insert into concepts (slug, title, short_explanation, full_explanation, test_question, red_pattern, green_pattern, failure_anecdote, tier, sort_order) values

('product_truth',
 'So you think you have a product',
 'A technical capability is not a product. A product is a capability that solves a quantified business problem for a specific buyer who has budget, urgency, and authority. Most STEM founders have built the first thing. They assume the second follows. It doesn''t.',
 E'## So you think you have a product\n\nYou have spent months or years building something technically impressive. It works. It is accurate, fast, elegant. Your early users — usually technical peers — think it is exciting. You are now trying to sell it to enterprises.\n\nThis is where most technical founders discover that a working technology is not the same thing as a product.\n\n### The definition that matters commercially\n\nA product, in the commercial sense, has four properties:\n\n1. **It solves a specific problem** — not a category of problems, not a vague pain, but a named, concrete problem that specific people have.\n2. **The problem has a cost** — in money, time, risk, or missed opportunity. The buyer knows this cost and can articulate it.\n3. **There is a defined buyer** — a person with a job title, a budget, and accountability for the problem. Not "enterprises" or "companies with data teams."\n4. **The buyer has urgency** — something has changed, is about to change, or is about to break that makes solving the problem now more important than solving it later.\n\n### Why technical founders skip this\n\nBuilding the technology is hard and satisfying. Defining the commercial product is uncomfortable — it requires admitting that not everyone has the problem, that most people with the problem are not urgent enough, and that you need to say no to many potential customers in order to say yes to the right ones.\n\nIt also requires conversations with buyers about their business problems rather than conversations with engineers about technical problems. These conversations are less comfortable and harder to prepare for.\n\n### The question you must be able to answer\n\n"Who specifically has this problem badly enough to spend £X to solve it this quarter — and what happened in their world that made this quarter the right quarter?"\n\nIf you cannot answer this question with a specific type of person (not a company, a person) and a specific trigger, you do not have a product yet. You have a technology looking for a product definition.',
 'Name the specific person (job title, industry, company size) who has this problem badly enough to pay for it this quarter — and what is happening in their world that makes this quarter the right time?',
 'The founder describes their product as solving a broad problem ("improving data quality," "automating workflows") for a broad market ("enterprises," "companies with AI teams"). When asked who the ideal first customer is, the answer is a company type, not a person. There is no articulated trigger for urgency.',
 'The founder can name a specific person (e.g., "Head of Financial Reporting at a UK insurance company with 500+ employees whose manual reconciliation process breaks every quarter-end") and a specific trigger ("the FCA''s new reporting requirements coming into force in Q1 mean their current process will not scale"). The ideal customer is a person, not a company.',
 'A founder built a document processing tool that genuinely worked better than anything on the market. They described it as "AI-powered document intelligence for enterprises." They spoke to 40 companies in their first year. They got interest from legal teams, finance teams, operations teams, HR teams. Everyone saw potential. Nobody signed. Eighteen months in, they narrowed to one vertical: insurance claims processing, specifically personal injury claims at insurers with 50k+ claims/year. They closed three customers in the next quarter. The technology had not changed. The product — the defined problem, buyer, and trigger — had finally been specified.',
 -1, 10),

('value_quantification',
 'Quantifying your value',
 'You need a number before you enter a deal — not after. "Improves efficiency" is not a business case. A specific improvement multiplied by the customer''s specific cost is. STEM founders are comfortable estimating technical performance. Estimating business impact requires a different set of questions.',
 E'## Quantifying your value\n\nEvery enterprise purchase is justified by a number. The CFO who approves your contract needs to be able to explain to the board why this expenditure was worthwhile. "The team finds it useful" does not justify £120k/year. "It eliminated 3 FTEs of manual work, saving £180k/year against a cost of £120k" does.\n\nYour job, before you walk into a sales conversation, is to know the structure of this number for your product.\n\n### The value equation structure\n\nMost B2B product value fits one of these patterns:\n\n**Cost reduction**: (current cost of doing X) × (your reduction rate) = annual saving\n*Example: 8 FTEs × £45k/year × 60% time saved = £216k/year*\n\n**Revenue impact**: (volume of decisions/actions affected) × (improvement in conversion/accuracy) × (value per unit) = revenue increase\n*Example: 50k decisions/month × 2% accuracy improvement × £150 value per correct decision = £180k/month*\n\n**Risk reduction**: (probability of bad event) × (cost of bad event) × (your reduction in probability) = expected value saved\n*Example: 3 compliance incidents/year × £500k average penalty × 70% reduction = £1.05M/year*\n\n**Time to value**: (weeks saved per project) × (projects per year) × (cost per week of project team) = opportunity value\n*Example: 4 weeks saved × 12 projects/year × £15k/week = £720k/year*\n\n### You provide the structure; the customer provides the numbers\n\nYou should never guess the customer''s numbers. You provide the formula; they fill in the blanks from their own data. "Help me understand your current process — how many people are involved, and roughly how much time does it take?" This is a question the customer can answer. "What is the cost of your current process?" is a question that puts them on the spot.\n\n### Why you need this before the deal, not in the deal\n\nIf you do not know the value structure, you cannot run a qualification conversation with confidence. You will avoid talking about money. You will describe features instead of outcomes. You will send a proposal with a price and no business case. The customer will ask "can you help us think through the ROI?" and you will not know where to start.',
 'For your product, what is the specific business outcome (in cost, revenue, or risk terms) that you can quantify — and what data from the customer do you need to calculate it?',
 'The founder describes value in feature terms: "it''s 40% more accurate than the alternative." When asked what that accuracy improvement is worth in business terms, they cannot calculate it. Proposals go out without a financial business case. The founder avoids talking about money because they are not sure what the product is worth.',
 'The founder has a value calculation framework: a formula with their known improvement rate and placeholders for the customer''s numbers (headcount, volume, cost per error, etc.). They can run this calculation in a discovery call. Their proposals include a business case section with the customer''s own numbers filled in.',
 'A founder built a legal contract review tool that reduced review time by 65%. They knew this from their beta tests. What they did not know was how to translate it into a business case. Their proposals said "reduces contract review time by 65%." Customers would nod and then not move forward. A year in, they learned to ask during discovery: "How many contracts does your legal team review per month, and roughly how long does each take?" With those numbers (120 contracts/month, 3 hours each), they could calculate: 65% × 120 × 3 hours × £120/hour = £28k/month in capacity freed. Proposals with this calculation converted at 3× the rate of proposals without it.',
 -1, 20),

('ideal_customer_profile',
 'Your ideal customer profile',
 'An ICP is not a target market. It is the specific description of the customer who has your problem most acutely, can buy fastest, and is most likely to expand. Without a tight ICP, you qualify everything, pursue anything, and close nothing.',
 E'## Your ideal customer profile\n\nAn Ideal Customer Profile (ICP) is a precise description of the customer for whom your product delivers the most value, most quickly, with the fewest complications. It is not a market segment. It is a set of specific characteristics that, when present together, predict a successful sale.\n\n### What a real ICP includes\n\nA useful ICP specifies:\n\n**Company characteristics**\n- Industry (specific, not "B2B")\n- Size (headcount or revenue range)\n- Geography (if relevant)\n- Maturity/stage (startup, scale-up, enterprise)\n- Technology profile (tech-forward, cloud-native, legacy infrastructure)\n\n**Trigger event** (critical, often missing)\nWhat has happened or is about to happen that makes this company need your product NOW? Triggers might include: regulatory change, leadership change, failed incumbent product, growth inflection point, competitive threat, M&A activity.\n\n**Buyer persona**\n- Specific job title and level\n- What they are measured on\n- What keeps them up at night\n- Why they would champion this internally\n\n**Negative ICP** (equally important)\nWho looks like your customer but is not — and why? Companies that will want a custom build, want to own the IP, have a procurement process that takes 18 months, or have the problem but no urgency to solve it. Time spent on negative ICP customers is the most expensive time in enterprise sales.\n\n### How the ICP is derived\n\nThe ICP is not invented. It is discovered from your first customers: who bought fastest, who got the most value, who expanded, who referred others. If you do not have enough customers to derive it empirically, start narrow and deliberately — pick the profile you believe is most likely and run three to five serious conversations before widening.',
 'Describe the company that would buy your product fastest, get the most value, and expand most significantly — what are the three or four specific characteristics that define them, and what has to have happened recently to put them in market?',
 'The founder describes their target as "mid-size enterprises" or "companies with data teams." They are pursuing any inbound lead regardless of fit. They are spending equal time on a 50-person startup and a 50,000-person enterprise. They have never explicitly defined who they are NOT targeting.',
 'The founder can describe their ICP in one paragraph with: specific industry, specific size range, specific job title of buyer, the trigger event that creates urgency, and the negative ICP. They use this to filter leads rather than pursue everything.',
 'A founder spent a year selling a supply chain optimisation tool to anyone who expressed interest: retailers, manufacturers, distributors, logistics companies. They had 25 active conversations at any given time. They closed four deals in twelve months. When they sat down and mapped which deals had closed, which had stalled, and which had expanded, a pattern emerged: all four closed deals were UK-based food and beverage manufacturers with 200–2000 employees who had experienced a supply disruption in the previous six months. That was the ICP. They stopped pursuing everyone else. In the following six months, they closed seven deals.',
 -1, 30),

('status_quo_competition',
 'The status quo is your real competitor',
 'In most B2B deals, you are not primarily competing against another vendor. You are competing against the way things are done today. Understanding why the status quo is good enough — and why it is about to fail — is more important than understanding any named competitor.',
 E'## The status quo is your real competitor\n\nTechnical founders prepare for competitive questions by studying other vendors. They compare features, benchmark performance, and prepare objection responses. This preparation is useful but incomplete. In most enterprise deals, the most likely outcome is not "they chose our competitor." It is "they decided not to change anything."\n\nThe status quo wins more deals than any named competitor.\n\n### Why the status quo is so powerful\n\n**Switching costs are real and visible.** Changing a process requires training, migration, integration work, risk, and change management. The new product has to be worth all of that — and the cost of not buying is invisible until it isn''t.\n\n**Inertia has no sales team.** The incumbent process does not send follow-up emails, does not run champions, does not build business cases. But it benefits from the human default to avoid change unless the pain of staying becomes greater than the pain of moving.\n\n**"We could build this."** For AI products especially, the internal build option is always present. It is almost always undercosted — engineers are optimistic, maintenance costs are invisible, opportunity costs are ignored. But as a competitive threat, it feels controllable and safe to a buyer in a way that an external vendor does not.\n\n### How to compete with the status quo\n\nThe status quo has three weaknesses you can exploit:\n\n1. **It does not scale.** If the customer is growing, their current process will break at some point. Your job is to make that breaking point visible and near.\n2. **It has a known, calculable cost.** The cost of manual work, the cost of errors, the cost of slow decisions — these can all be calculated. Make the cost of the status quo explicit and documented.\n3. **Something has changed.** The reason anyone is talking to you at all is that the status quo has become insufficient for some reason. Find that trigger and make it the centre of the conversation.\n\n### The build vs. buy question\n\nWhen a customer says "we could build this," the right response is a calculation, not an argument. Ask: "How many engineers would you put on it, and for how long?" Then: "And what would they not be building during that time?" Most builds look different when the opportunity cost is included.',
 'If your team decided today to keep doing what you''re doing rather than buying anything, what would that cost you over the next 12 months — and what would have to be true for that to become unacceptable?',
 'The founder''s competitive preparation focuses entirely on named vendors. They cannot explain why the customer''s current process is failing or is about to fail. They have no calculation of the cost of doing nothing. Their pitch focuses on product features rather than the cost of staying still.',
 'The founder can articulate exactly why the status quo is becoming untenable for their ICP: what is changing in the customer''s environment, what the current process costs, and at what point the cost of doing nothing exceeds the cost and friction of switching. They lead with this, not with features.',
 'A founder was consistently losing deals "to budget constraints." On closer examination, the deals were not lost to budget — they were lost to inertia. Customers had enough pain to talk to the founder but not enough pain to authorise a change. The founder started asking a different question in qualification: "What happens to your team if this problem is not solved by [specific date]?" The deals where the customer could answer this question concretely were the deals that closed. The deals where the customer said "it''s not ideal but we''d manage" were the deals that would never close, regardless of feature comparisons or pricing.',
 -1, 40),

('value_based_pricing',
 'Value-based pricing',
 'Price to the value you deliver, not to the cost of building it or the time you spent. A product that saves a customer £500k/year should not be priced at £20k because that felt "safe." Your price is a signal of your product''s seriousness — and of yours.',
 E'## Value-based pricing\n\nMost technical founders price their product one of two ways: cost-plus (what did it cost me to build, plus a margin?) or market-reference (what is the competitor charging?). Both methods anchor the price to the wrong thing.\n\nValue-based pricing anchors the price to what the product is worth to the customer — specifically, to a fraction of the value it delivers.\n\n### The pricing fraction\n\nEnterprise software typically captures between 10% and 30% of the value it delivers. A product that saves a customer £400k/year in operational cost is reasonably priced between £40k and £120k/year. The exact fraction depends on:\n- How certain is the value? (Proven ROI commands higher fractions)\n- How easily can the customer get this value elsewhere? (Uniqueness commands higher fractions)\n- How embedded does the product become? (Switching cost supports higher fractions)\n- How large is the customer? (Larger organisations can afford higher ACV for equivalent ROI)\n\n### Why founders underprice\n\nThree reasons:\n\n**Fear of losing the deal.** If you price low, you cannot be rejected on price. But low prices attract price-sensitive buyers who will always find a cheaper option, require more hand-holding, and generate the worst reference customers.\n\n**Not knowing the value.** If you have not done the work to quantify the value you deliver (see: Quantifying your value), you cannot price to it. You will default to cost-plus or market-reference because you have no other anchor.\n\n**Confusing affordable with fair.** "They can afford £10k" is not a pricing rationale. "We deliver £200k of value; 10% of that is £20k, so £20k is the right price" is a pricing rationale.\n\n### What your price signals\n\nPrice is information. A price that is significantly below market signals one of three things: the product is not differentiated, the founder lacks confidence in the value, or the product is early and not enterprise-ready. None of these are signals you want to send to an Economic Buyer who is being asked to trust you with a significant process.\n\n### The conversation to have\n\nEstablish the value calculation with the customer BEFORE you present a price. If the customer agrees that their problem costs £400k/year and your product reduces that by 50%, you are discussing a £200k value. Then a price of £60k/year is obviously justified. A price presented without a value anchor forces the buyer to evaluate it against their own (lower) reference points.',
 'If we can show that your problem costs approximately £X/year and our product reduces that by Y%, what fraction of that saving would represent fair value for the solution?',
 'The founder''s price was set by looking at competitor pricing or by calculating their costs. The pricing page shows a low number because "we need to be accessible." When asked why the product is priced at £X, the founder cannot explain it in terms of the value delivered. The first enterprise prospect asked for a discount and got one immediately.',
 'The price is derived from value: the founder can explain the value calculation and show that the price is a specific fraction (typically 15–25%) of the documented value delivered. Discounts are made against something — a multi-year commitment, a reference agreement, an accelerated close — not just because someone asked.',
 'A founder priced their AI-powered compliance tool at £12k/year because "that seemed like what SMEs could afford." Their first enterprise customer — a mid-size bank — signed without negotiating. At the first renewal, the customer''s new procurement lead asked for the value assessment. The founder put together the calculation for the first time: the tool was preventing approximately 8 compliance incidents per year, at an average cost of £75k each. That was £600k/year in risk reduction. The customer''s £12k price was 2% of the value. At renewal, the founder repriced to £90k/year — 15% of the value — and the customer agreed it was reasonable. The original price had been set without any reference to value.',
 -1, 50),

('pricing_signals',
 'What your price says about your product',
 'Price is not just a commercial term — it is a signal. A price that is too low signals that the product is not serious, not differentiated, or not enterprise-ready. A price that is too high without a value case signals arrogance. The right price, explained with a value rationale, signals a vendor worth dealing with.',
 E'## What your price says about your product\n\nEnterprise buyers are sophisticated. They see many vendors. They have learned to interpret price signals the way an investor interprets a valuation: not just as a number, but as a claim about what the thing is worth and who it is for.\n\n### The low-price trap\n\nA price that is significantly below market or that the buyer finds surprisingly affordable does not generate relief. It generates doubt. "Why is it so cheap?" is a question buyers ask, even if they do not say it aloud. The answers they imagine are rarely flattering: the product is immature, the company is desperate, there is a catch, others have not bought it at this price so maybe it is not ready.\n\nLow prices also attract the wrong customers: organisations that are optimising for cost, not for value. These customers will renegotiate aggressively at renewal, demand the most support, generate the least useful feedback, and make the worst reference accounts.\n\n### The high-price-without-justification trap\n\nA price that is significantly above what the customer expects, without a clear value rationale, generates a different problem: the buyer assumes you are taking advantage of information asymmetry. They know the product is probably worth it for someone — but they are not sure it is worth it for them, and they do not trust you to tell them honestly.\n\n### The right price, explained\n\nA price that is explained in terms of value — "we typically price at 15–20% of the documented cost saving, which for your situation puts us at £X" — is a price the buyer can evaluate rationally. They can agree or disagree with the fraction. They can challenge the value estimate. But the conversation is about business outcomes, not about whether you deserve the money.\n\n### Pricing as qualification\n\nPrice is also a qualification tool. Sharing your price range early in a conversation — not the final price, but the range — surfaces budget constraints before you invest significant time. A customer who is not in budget is better to disqualify in week one than in week twelve.\n\n### Discounting\n\nEvery discount should be traded for something: a multi-year commitment, a reference agreement, an accelerated close, a case study right, a mutual action plan commitment. Discounts given without any exchange tell the customer two things: the original price was inflated, and you will discount again if they push.',
 'When you present your price, can you explain it as a fraction of the value it delivers — and what specifically does a customer get by paying full price versus asking for a discount?',
 'The founder discounts when asked, without requiring anything in exchange. Different customers are paying significantly different prices for the same product without a structural reason. The founder cannot explain their price in terms of value delivered. Price objections cause anxiety rather than a structured response.',
 'The price is explained before it is presented: value is established, fraction is stated, price follows logically. Discounts are traded: early close gets X% off, three-year commitment gets Y% off, reference customer gets Z% off. Every customer knows what they are getting and what they are trading for it.',
 'A founder gave a 30% discount to their second enterprise customer because "they pushed back hard." Their third customer — who had not pushed back — later discovered the pricing discrepancy through a mutual contact. They demanded the same discount retroactively. The founder, having set no pricing principle, had no basis to refuse. They lost margin on both deals and created a precedent of discounting on request that followed them into every subsequent negotiation.',
 -1, 60),

('deal_structure',
 'Deal structure: ACV, TCV, and how you frame the number',
 'How you structure a deal — annual vs. multi-year, ACV vs. TCV, included services vs. professional fees — changes what the buyer compares you to and what they have to approve. Understanding deal structure is not a finance exercise. It is a sales strategy.',
 E'## Deal structure: ACV, TCV, and how you frame the number\n\nThe same commercial relationship can be presented as a £30k/year subscription, a £90k three-year contract, or a £70k first-year engagement including implementation. These are not the same deal. They go through different approval processes, compete with different alternatives, and create different renewal dynamics.\n\n### Key terms\n\n**ACV (Annual Contract Value)**: The annualised value of the contract, regardless of length. A £90k three-year deal has an ACV of £30k.\n\n**TCV (Total Contract Value)**: The total value over the contract term. A £30k/year three-year deal has a TCV of £90k.\n\n**NRE (Non-Recurring Engineering)**: One-time fees for custom work, integration, or implementation. These are separate from the recurring subscription and go through a different budget process.\n\n### How structure affects approval\n\nMost organisations have approval thresholds by value:\n- Under £25k: manager approval\n- £25k–£100k: director or VP approval\n- £100k+: C-suite or board approval\n\nA deal structured as a three-year £120k TCV (£40k ACV) may require C-suite approval. The same deal structured as a £40k/year annual subscription may require only VP approval — and be easier to start, with the option to sign a multi-year at renewal.\n\nThis is not about avoiding scrutiny. It is about matching the deal structure to the buyer''s internal process so the right person can approve it at the right speed.\n\n### Multi-year deals\n\nA multi-year deal benefits you (revenue predictability, reduced churn risk) and can benefit the buyer (price certainty, often a discount). But a multi-year deal requires a higher-level approval. Structure multi-year deals for customers where:\n- The EB is already engaged and supportive\n- The paper process is not a bottleneck\n- The value is well-established and the ROI case is strong\n\nFor a customer who is new and cautious, an annual deal with a clear renewal path is often faster to close.\n\n### Professional services and NRE\n\nImplementation fees, integration work, and custom development are often a necessary part of an enterprise sale — but they complicate the commercial structure. Keep professional services clearly separated from the recurring subscription in your proposals. Many organisations budget OpEx (subscription) and CapEx (implementation) differently. Conflating them can stall a deal that would otherwise move quickly.',
 'Given your internal approval thresholds and budget cycle, what deal structure would allow the right person to sign this quickly — and what would a multi-year commitment look like if the first year goes well?',
 'The founder presents a single price with no discussion of structure. When a deal stalls, they do not consider whether restructuring might help it move. All deals are annual because "that is our standard." The founder does not know the customer''s approval thresholds.',
 'The founder understands the customer''s approval process and tailors the deal structure accordingly. They can articulate what the customer gets from a multi-year commitment and why a particular structure is recommended for this specific customer''s situation.',
 'A founder was stuck on a £150k/year deal for three months. The VP of Engineering wanted to buy but kept saying "we''re working through the approval process." The founder eventually discovered that any contract over £100k required board approval at this company, and the board only met quarterly. The next meeting was six weeks away. The founder offered to restructure: £95k/year for the first year with a pre-agreed option to move to a three-year term at renewal. The VP approved it the following week. The deal that had been stalled for three months closed in three days once the structure matched the approval process.',
 -1, 70),

('margin_benchmarks',
 'What good margins look like: software, AI, services, hardware',
 'Gross margin is not just an accounting number — it is a signal of business model quality. Investors, acquirers, and sophisticated customers use it to assess whether your product is a real product or a services business in disguise. Knowing the benchmarks tells you where you stand.',
 E'## What good margins look like\n\nGross margin — revenue minus the direct cost of delivering that revenue — is the single most important indicator of business model quality in B2B technology. It determines how much capital you need to grow, how attractive you are to investors, and how much pricing power you have.\n\n### Benchmarks by business type\n\n**Pure software (SaaS)**\nGood: 75–85% gross margin. Great: 85%+.\nThe economics are exceptional because incremental delivery costs are near zero. Once built, serving the next customer costs almost nothing. Most of the cost is in sales and R&D, which are operating expenses, not cost of goods sold.\n\n**AI software with significant inference cost**\nGood: 60–75% gross margin. Great: 75%+.\nThe GPU/compute cost of inference is real and significant for AI products, especially those with high-volume or complex model calls. Founders often underestimate this — "we''ll optimise later" — and discover that their gross margin at scale is 50% rather than 80%. Know your inference cost per customer before you set your price.\n\n**Services-led or implementation-heavy**\nGood: 40–60% gross margin. Acceptable: 30–40%.\nIf every customer requires significant professional services — integration work, configuration, training — delivered by humans, your gross margin will look more like a services firm than a software firm. This is not fatal, but it affects your valuation multiple and your ability to scale without proportional headcount growth.\n\n**AI agents / autonomous workflows**\nEmergent benchmark: 50–70% gross margin at scale.\nAgent products have variable cost structures — each task runs model calls, sometimes hundreds per job. Margin depends heavily on: task complexity, model choice, caching, and whether you can build proprietary efficiency advantages. This category is still being benchmarked by the market.\n\n**Hardware or hardware-enabled products**\nGood: 40–60% gross margin on the hardware, supplemented by high-margin software/services. Great: if hardware is break-even and software/service contracts are the real margin engine.\nHardware companies are valued as hardware companies (lower multiples) until the software/services revenue is dominant. The strategic goal is to use hardware as a distribution mechanism for high-margin recurring software.\n\n### Why this matters for founders selling to enterprises\n\nSophisticated buyers — especially those who have bought technology before — will ask about your business model. A customer who is signing a three-year contract wants to know you will still be around. A customer who is evaluating a strategic technology partnership wants to know your model is sustainable.\n\nKnowing your gross margin and being able to explain it signals that you understand your business. Not knowing it signals that you may be running on enthusiasm rather than economics.\n\n### The services trap\n\nThe most common margin-destroying pattern for STEM founders: building a general-purpose platform that requires significant custom work for each customer. Each deal looks big — £150k, £200k — but a third of it is professional services at 30% margin. The underlying software ACV is £100k at 80% margin; the services revenue is dragging the blended margin to 60%. The fix is to productise the common services, build them into the platform, and charge for them as software.',
 'What is your estimated gross margin per customer — and have you included your true cost of delivery (compute, support, implementation, account management)?',
 'The founder does not know their gross margin. They price based on ACV without understanding what it costs to deliver the contract. Professional services are bundled into deals without tracking their margin separately. Compute costs for AI inference are not modelled as a cost of goods.',
 'The founder knows their blended gross margin and can break it down by component: software margin, services margin, compute cost as a % of revenue. They know their target margin and what needs to happen to reach it. They track gross margin per customer cohort.',
 'A founder celebrated a £200k enterprise deal. Six months in, they did a proper cost accounting exercise. The deal included £60k of implementation work delivered by two engineers for three months — at fully loaded cost, that was £45k. The software subscription was £140k/year, but required £30k/year of compute and £20k of ongoing support. Gross margin on the full deal in year one: (£200k revenue - £45k implementation - £30k compute - £20k support) / £200k = 52.5%. Not terrible, but the founder had been presenting to investors as an "80% gross margin SaaS business." The implementation costs were invisible to them until someone asked.',
 -1, 80);


